<p>Say I have an index (col1, col2, col3), which enables indexed search on these queries:</p>  <pre><code>WHERE col1 = xxx WHERE col1 = xxx AND col2 = yyy WHERE col1 = xxx AND col2 = yyy AND AND col3 = zzz </code></pre>  <p>If I want to search by</p>  <pre><code>WHERE col2 = yyy AND col3 = zzz WHERE col3 = zzz </code></pre>  <p>I would have to create these indexes:</p>  <pre><code>(col2, col3) (col3) </code></pre>  <p>Right?</p>  <p>But do I have to create yet another index if I want to search by:</p>  <pre><code>WHERE col1 = yyy AND col3 = zzz </code></pre>  <p>?</p>  <p>I tried to search for an answer but found nothing about searching on non-consecutive columns in an index, such as <a href="https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.0/en/multiple-column-indexes.html" rel="nofollow">here</a>.</p>  <p>Does MySQL use (col1, col2, col3) for this or do I have to create (col1, col3)?</p>